The paper deals with computational complexity in a voting setting, which is a classic topic in computational social choice (cs.GT). The problem involves selecting a subset of candidates based on voter approvals, which can be modeled as a combinatorial optimization problem (cs.DS). The paper also discusses algorithms for achieving the proportional justified representation property, which involves balancing the representation of different groups of voters, and this is a common problem in machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.AI, cs.LG). Finally, the paper discusses the complexity of the problem under different parameter settings, which is a common approach in algorithmic game theory and computational social choice (cs.SI).
